<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAR 93 / Scots TUC urges peaceful demonstration at Timex
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS WERE last night making urgent efforts to avoid a repetition of last
Monday's violent picketing outside the Timex factory in Dundee, where the
US-owned company last month sacked and re-placed its workforce after a
strike.
This came as the Court of Session in Edinburgh granted a new interdict
(injunction) to Timex limiting the number of pickets outside the plant to
six and requiring picketing to be peaceful. The AEEU had appealed against a
similar interdict granted to the company earlier in the month.
Mr Campbell Christie, general secretary of the Scottish Trade Union
Congress, urged people planning to take part in next Monday's demonstration
to stay within the law and keep to the rules set by the AEEU engineering and
electrical union, which is involved in the dispute. He said: 'We will not
welcome anyone coming to Timex who does not accept the discipline of the
AEEU. Anyone not prepared to do so should stay away.'
The appeal, made after talks with Tayside police, was aimed at leftwing
groups such as Scottish Militant Labour, which took part in last Monday's
picketing in which 16 people were arrested when 600 demonstrators battled
with police.
But Scottish Militant Labour said it again planned to bus in supporters from
other parts of Scotland to join the picket line on Monday and appealed to
other groups to follow suit.
Mr Tommy Sheridan, leader of Scottish Militant Labour, who was arrested in
last Monday's clashes, said he would be in Dundee but not at the picket
line. Last Tuesday he appeared in court accused of breach of the peace and
was ordered not to go within a mile of the plant.
At a news conference in Glasgow he quoted an appeal from Mr John Kydd, the
sacked Timex union convener, for trade unionists, political parties 'and any
individuals the length of breadth of Britain' to support the Monday picket.
The violent picketing last Monday is embarrassing to the unions which, while
backing the sacked workforce, see little chance of winning the dispute and
do not wish to be associated with either Militant or violence.
Last night Timex welcomed the STUC statement and said that if there was
compliance with it and with the new interdict 'there ought to be no
repetition of the violent and disorderly behaviour' to which its employees
had been subjected.
</TEXT>
