<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAR 93 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Entitled to benefit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
HAVING BOUGHT Treasury 8 per cent 2009 on the National Savings register, I
was charged Pounds 309.10 for 138 days' accrued interest (gross). Can I
offset this against the first payment of gross interest, and account to the
Inland Revenue only for tax on the difference?
Also, having bought some Inchcape 12 1/2 per cent ULS and Bristol &amp; West
Pibs, I was charged a total of Pounds 354.40 as accrued interest. When I
receive payment of the first interests, they will be paid net - which, of
course, covers the accrued periods. Have I a claim for recovery of tax on
the Pounds 354.40?
Although you forgot to tell us the nominal amount of each holding, it is
clear that the total nominal amount exceeds Pounds 5,000. That being so, you
are entitled to the benefit of the accrued-income scheme (AIS), and can
claim the appropriate relief in your next tax return. Meanwhile, ask your
tax office for the free pamphlet on the AIS: IR68.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
