FT  27 MAR 93 / Mining equipment sector fears loss of 9,000 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE MINING equipment industry faces the loss of 9,000 jobs
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
40 per cent of its workforce - because of the government's plans for the
future of the coal industry, the Association of British Mining Equipment
Companies said yesterday.
The cutting of a world-leading industry's base could cause foreign buyers to
lose confidence in its ability to maintain capacity, the association warned.
A 'disappointing' white paper offered little prospect of increased demand
for coal, it added. Mr William Morrell, association director-general, warned
that equipment manufacturers with overseas factories could also transfer
work to countries where there is an active coalfield. The UK leads the world
equipment market for longwall mining - the UK system of extracting coal in a
continuous run of 200 metres to 300 metres. Exports have risen significantly
over the past five years, accounting for about Pounds 400m of total
production worth about Pounds 900m a year.
The association warned that a sizeable and stable home market was essential
for continuing international marketing success. This was needed to finance
spending on research and development and application technology.
British Coal has traditionally been the equipment industry's principal
customer. The association said its members' state-of-the-art technology had
been a significant contributor to British Coal's 160 per cent increase in
productivity since 1986. The recent decline in the UK coal industry had
taken its toll on equipment suppliers. The association said the closure of
70 per cent of UK mines from end-1987 to end-1991 had reduced the direct
workforce by 50,000 to 22,000.
The association said yesterday that, by taking 18 pits out of production,
the government would remove one third of the suppliers' domestic market,
giving no time for companies to adapt.
The association said many companies will not be able to sustain the research
and development necessary for continued export success, adding: 'Perhaps
most importantly, the government still does not have a long-term energy
policy which makes it impossible for our industry to plan what demand is
likely to be for its products.'
