<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAR 93 / Unit trust funds at record Pounds 69.2bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AMOUNT of money invested in unit trusts increased to a record Pounds
69.2bn at the end of February, as buoyant stock markets and falling interest
rates encouraged investors to buy collective funds, Philip Coggan writes.
Gross sales of unit trusts in February were Pounds 1.3bn, the highest figure
since Pounds 1.7bn in September 1987. After allowing for repurchases of
Pounds 738.3m, net investment was Pounds 590.7m, compared with Pounds 509m
in Jan-uary.
The industry was also boosted by strong sales of personal equity plans
(Peps) as the end of the tax year approached. More than Pounds 53m was
invested in UK equity income funds. Income and gains within Peps are
tax-free.
Even more encouraging for the industry was that the number of unit-holder
accounts, which had been steadily declining since 1987, has started to
increase.
At the end of February the number of accounts was 4.4m compared with 4.35m
last year.
However, institutional investment provided almost Pounds 400m of February's
net sales. The Budget change to advance corporation tax has raised fears
that life insurance companies will find it less tax-efficient to invest in
unit trusts. The industry is lobbying the Treasury to try to prevent the
problem.
The Budget also reduced the tax advantage of a Pep for a basic-rate
taxpayer.
</TEXT>
