<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / US House Speaker hits at Ulster violence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Thomas Foley, Speaker of the US House of Representatives, yesterday
issued a vigorous condemnation of violence by both republican and unionist
terrorists in Northern Ireland and called for the resumption of political
talks on the province's future.
Coming from a prominent Roman Catholic politician of Irish ancestry, the
statement was warmly welcomed by the UK government, which has been nervous
about US policy on Northern Ireland since Mr Bill Clinton, in last year's
American presidential campaign, called for the appointment of a US special
envoy to the province.
Mr Foley attacked the bomb planted by the Irish Republican Army which last
week killled a child in Warrington as 'senseless savagery', and condemned
the bombing this week by the Ulster Freedom Fighters of homes of Sinn Fein
councillors in Northern Ireland.
But he also added blunt criticism of US groups which raise money for Irish
terrorist groups.
'These villainous attacks are a grim and signal lesson to anyone who,
through financial or other assistance, supports groups and organisations
supplying the wherewithal to perpetrate the terrorist's cowardly, despicable
attacks against humanity,' Mr Foley said.
British Prime Minister John Major tried to deflect Mr Clinton from
appointing a special envoy when he visited Washington last month, but the US
president said last week, during a visit by Irish Prime Minister Albert
Reynolds, that he was still giving 'serious consideration' to the idea.
Indeed, Mr Foley's name was one of those mentioned as a possible envoy,
although the speaker's office made it clear he was too busy shepherding Mr
Clinton's legislative programme through Congress to take on another role.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, yesterday warmly welcomed Mr
Foley's statement, calling his words 'very wise'.
</TEXT>
