<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / International Company News: Cuomo backs Murdoch bid to
acquire NY Post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BATTLE for the New York Post, the bankrupt tabloid newspaper, took a new
twist yesterday as it emerged that Mr Rupert Murdoch had won the support of
New York Governor Mario Cuomo and two US Senators in his bid to acquire The
Post.
Mr Murdoch, who owned The Post between 1976 and 1988, is seeking a waiver of
the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) regulation that bans anyone from
owning both a newspaper and a television station in the same city. Mr
Murdoch's Fox television network owns a New York station.
Governor Cuomo, in a letter sent to Mr John Dingell, chairman of the
Congressional committee with jurisdiction over the FCC, argued in favour of
a waiver for Mr Murdoch, although he added: 'I anticipate that under the
prospective ownership of Rupert Murdoch I will continue to find myself at
odds with The Post's coverage.'
Mr Murdoch has the 'right of first refusal' to buy The Post if its present
owner - Mr Peter Kalikow, a bankrupt property developer - decides to sell.
The Post saga became more muddled still yesterday when another bidder for
the newspaper - Mr Steven Hoffenberg, the debt collector who is being sued
for fraud by the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) - was told by a
federal court judge to provide a full accounting of his personal and
business assets within 10 days or face arrest.
The unusual court order, which concerns Dollars 1.4m of cheques written by
Mr Hoffenberg to The New York Post and to a company he controls, came as Mr
Hoffenberg sought bankruptcy protection for five subsidiaries of his debt
collection agency - Towers Financial.
Mr Abe Hirschfeld, the car parks magnate who currently controls The Post and
was until recently Mr Hoffenberg's main partner, was meanwhile enmeshed in
yet another of what have become almost daily battles with Mr Pete Hamill,
the mutinous and yet highly popular editor of the newspaper.
The newspaper has been traumatised over the past fortnight by the arrival of
the 73-year-old Mr Hirschfeld, an eccentric who has sacked and re-hired a
number of staff, including Mr Hamill.
</TEXT>
