FT  26 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Major reaffirms government's
commitment to reducing basic rate of income tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday reaffirmed the government's commitment to reducing
the basic rate of income tax to 20 pence, Ivor Owen writes. The prime
minister said it was proposed to extend the current 20p rate band as
'rapidly and as prudently' as possible.
To Labour cheers, Mr Elliot Morley, MP for Glanford and Scunthorpe, claimed
that for most people total taxation was now far higher than when the last
Labour government left office in 1979. He said the action taken in the
Budget to extend value added tax to domestic fuel would have a crippling
effect on many people with small occupational pensions which took them just
above the income support level.
The prime minister retored that if Mr Morley was really concerned about the
tax burden he should dissociate himself from the demands for increased
public expenditure repeatedly made from the Labour benches.
