<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Competition policy doubted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LACK of a cohesive approach by the competition authorities to defining
markets is producing inconsistencies in the vetting of monopolies and
mergers, research published yesterday by the Office of Fair Trading shows.
The research, carried out for the OFT by economic consultants Nera, says a
company's 'market share' is invariably quoted by the OFT and the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission to justify a decision to block a merger on
competition grounds or to infer that a company enjoys a dominant market
position.
But the question of how the particular market is defined is rarely addressed
explicitly and there are inconsistencies in approach between one case and
another, the report says.
The MMC's approach to defining markets in cases involving secondary products
(spare parts) has varied considerably, it says. In two photocopier inquiries
the MMC concluded that the secondary products for toner and maintenance
formed part of the same product market as the photocopiers themselves. In a
Ford inquiry, however, the commission defined Ford body panels as a separate
relevant market.
Nera says that in an attempt to iron out such inconsistencies the OFT and
MMC should be obliged to define the relevant market as an explicit stage in
their analysis before using market shares to support their conclusions.
This would bring UK competition policy into line with EC competition law.
Nera notes that many different concepts of the term 'the market' exist.
It says the most useful concept of the relevant market identifies it
according to whether a single supplier of a particular product (or
hypothetical monopolist) would find it profitable to raise the price of that
product. If it would, the product represents a separate market. If not, the
product is part of a wider market.
It suggests an economic approach to market definition, including checklists
for dealing with specific problems such as deciding whether a market is
national or international, and assessing how similar two products need to be
in order to be classified in the same market.
Market Definition in UK Competition Policy. Office of Fair Trading, 53
Chancery Lane, London WC1. Free
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
