<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Finance summaries 'difficult to read'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUMMARY financial statements are often more difficult to read than a
company's full annual report, a study sponsored by the Institute of
Chartered Accountants in England and Wales says.
A desire to save costs is the main reason why companies offer shareholders
summary statements, says the report. However, it says, the profit and loss
account and balance sheets statements are normally identical to those
provided in the full accounts, but come without the notes.
Summary statements were introduced in the 1989 Companies Act. Companies can
send them to shareholders in place of the full accounts.
The survey, based on the experiences of 300 industrial and financial
companies, found that producing summary statements rarely saved money.
Summary Financial Statements. ICAEW, Moorgate Place, London EC2P 2BJ. Pounds
10.
</TEXT>
