<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Society fraudster jailed for five years
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DARIUS GUPPY, a society gems dealer turned fraudster, and Mr Benedict
Marsh, his business partner, were yesterday jailed for five years over a
bogus robbery and false insurance claim.
They were each fined Pounds 533,000 for conspiracy to steal Pounds 1.2m from
the gemstones company of which Mr Guppy was an executive director, and
warned that they would serve an extra three years if it was not paid within
six months.
The sentences came five weeks after the end of a three-month trial at
Snaresbrook Crown Court, east London.
Judge Andrew Brooks sentenced each man to five years for conspiracy to
defraud Lloyd's of London of Pounds 1.8m, five years concurrently for
conspiracy to steal Pounds 1.2m from their company - for which the Pounds
533,000 fine was also imposed - and 12 months concurrently for conspiracy to
commit false accounting.
They had pleaded not guilty at their trial to the three charges.
At a later hearing on March 4 Mr Guppy, who was best man at the wedding of
Earl Spencer, pleaded guilty to three charges of falsely claiming he was
entitled to repayment of VAT for bogus gold bullion exports, and Mr Marsh
pleaded guilty to one charge.
Yesterday the judge imposed a fine of Pounds 2,000, with an alternative of
45 days imprisonment, on each charge.
Judge Brooks also ordered that the two men be barred from being company
directors for at least 10 years.
</TEXT>
