FT  26 MAR 93 / EC social policy has impact on employers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community's social agenda has had a significant impact on
employers and unions in Britain in spite of government hostility to many
parts of it, according to a report from the Policy Studies Institute.
The report says unions are increasingly integrating ideas from the 1989
Social Charter into collective bargaining and strengthening links with other
unions in the EC.
It says employers are reviewing differing working conditions in their
organisations across the EC so as to be able to respond to comparison claims
from UK unions.
The report says unions and employers have been largely reactive to the EC's
social agenda and have played only a small role in setting it.
Trade Unions and Employers in the Single Europe. BEBC, PO Box 14965, Poole,
Dorset BH12 3YD. Pounds 10.
