<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Court threat over building society rents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BUILDING society which sold an estate agency chain that later went into
liquidation is facing demands for unpaid rents from landlords who insist it
is still legally responsible for its former subsidiary.
The claim against Northern Rock, Britain's 11th-largest building society,
comes from a group of landlords from whom estate agency offices were rented.
The claim hinges on Section 22 of the 1986 Building Societies Act, requiring
societies to discharge the liabilities of subsidiaries. The case is believed
to be the first of its kind.
Northern Rock, which has rejected the landlords' demand for rents totalling
more than Pounds 300,000, insists its obligation ceased when it sold the
chain last year. Mr Chris Jobe, society secretary, said: 'We believe that
when we dispose of a subsidiary company that liability ends.' But some
landlords and their legal advisers are meeting today to decide whether to
pursue their claim, possibly in the High Court.
Solicitor Mr Peter Hughes, at whose office the meeting will be held, said:
'It's a question of interpretation of the legislation and the surrounding
circumstances.'
Mr Hughes, a partner in Corbould Rigby &amp; Co, is acting for two landlords and
co-ordinating an investigation on behalf of 10 more.
Northern Rock Property Services, a subsidiary of the Newcastle-based
building society, built up an estate agency chain in the 1980s, trading
under different names in various parts of England. At its 1989 peak it had
about 100 outlets. As the property market slumped and the chain's generation
of mortgage business proved disappointing, Northern Rock decided to quit the
estate agency and sold the chain to several buyers.
In September last year 51 estate agency offices in London, the south-east
and on the south coast were sold, under the name Seleridge to a company
called Franklin Fox. Two months later Seleridge went into liquidation.
Mr Hughes said that in many cases leases entered into by Seleridge have been
disclaimed by the liquidator. Mr Chris Potter, former managing director of
defunct Northern Rock Property Services, said: 'The landlord has to take the
same chance as anybody else in commerce these days.'
Mr Michael Coogan, deputy secretary of the Building Societies Association,
said that to his knowledge the case was the first of its kind.
</TEXT>
