<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Study of finance regulators urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL REGULATORS have expanded into areas which should have nothing to
do with regulation and their activities need to be re-examined, says a
report from Professors Julian Franks and Stephen Schaefer of the London
Business School, released yesterday.
But they conclude that the direct costs of regulation in the UK are broadly
in line with costs in the US and France. The report is to be published on
April 2 as part of the City Research Project, set up to examine the
competitiveness of the UK as a base for financial services business.
Threats to investor protection in the past stemmed 'almost exclusively' from
fraud, misappropriation and malpractice, the two professors argue.
Regulation should be focused on these areas, they say, rather than on
improving standards in the industry or developing capital adequacy rules to
protect investors when an investment business is wound up. Their comments
precede publication of a far-reaching review of investment regulation by Mr
Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and Investments Board.
In the UK, there are about six regulators for every 1,000 people employed in
the securities industry, compared with nearly 12 in the US. Regulatory costs
total 0.53 per cent of the industry's costs, excluding interest expenses,
compared with 1.34 per cent in the US.
Investment management is more expensive to regulate in the UK, however.
Costs amount to 0.43 of a basis point (hundredth of a percentage point) of
funds under management, compared with 0.16 bp in the US and 0.11 bp in
France.
There are 6.8 regulators for every 1000 employees, compared with 1.7 in the
US and 1.3 in France.
The Costs and Effectiveness of the UK Financial Regulatory System.
Corporation of London. PO Box 270 Guildhall EC2P 2EJ.
</TEXT>
