<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / The Coal White Paper: Future for coal - Heseltine holds his
ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The story of the changes in the various coal proposals over the last five
months is primarily the story of how the government was persuaded it was
politically imperative to reprieve at least some of the 31 pits earmarked
for closure last October.
This is the effect of the subsidy proposals unveiled yesterday. The prospect
of 12 high-producing pits being saved looks to have staved off the worst of
the threatened backbench rebellion which nearly swamped the government in
the autumn.
But there is no guarantee of how long the reprieve will last and Mr
Heseltine has reserved the right to close 12 pits, to mothball a further six
and to retain one under development with production halted.
In short, the extent of the government's achievement in the white paper
could yet be confined to ensuring the closures announced in October are
phased in over a much longer period.
Yesterday's package bore a strong resemblance to last month's draft white
paper, with the important exception of the changes forced upon the
government as a result of its failure to win a commitment from the main
electricity generators to take more than the 160m tonnes of coal over five
years they had agreed.
This scuppered hopes that an additional short-term market for deep-mined
coal could be created by encouraging the generators to run higher stocks
than they had planned.
The government has also seen no need to impose a limit on open-cast coal
output, which it hinted at in the draft white paper, since such production
is expected to fall anyway.
Measures related to orimulsion were restricted to making its subject to
hydrocarbon duty, rather than forcing power stations burning the
bitumen-based fuel to fit flue gas desulphurisation equipment - a step
hinted at in the draft and recommended by the trade and industry select
committee.
The government decided to pass over the committee's most radical proposals -
postponing electricity market liberalisation, cutting the pounds 1.2bn
nuclear levy and cutting purchases of electricity from France - because of
its strong preference for avoiding legislation, except that needed to
privatise the industry.
It has stuck to its faith in the market as the ultimate arbiter of Britain's
energy mix, with little change from its position in October.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
