<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / The Coal White Paper: True contentment, but only for the
lucky few - How one miner found his 'dream' job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRIDING OVER the limestone grassland of Durham's coastline, Denis Rooney, a
former colliery fitter, cannot believe his luck.
After 18 years working underground he is now paid to roam the cliffs near
his home, protecting the scenery he loves. As National Trust warden for this
curious north-east coast, where dramatic cliffs and meadows studded with
orchids lead down to beaches black with coal waste, he has found job
satisfaction.
When his wife spotted the job advertisement in the Sunderland Echo Mr
Rooney, then 45 and unemployed, doubted his chances. 'I said 'everybody has
degrees who get those jobs'.'
Two years later the keen conservationist still cannot believe his good
fortune. 'I still haven't come off cloud nine, it's just a dream come true,'
he says.
Mr Rooney, last of a family of miners, decided in 1987 to take his
redundancy from Dawdon colliery - since closed and now the northern boundary
of his four-mile warden's beat. In the late 1980s it was easier for former
Durham miners to find work. But since mid 1991 Dawdon and Murton collieries
have closed, costing East Durham 2,000 jobs and creating a large pool of
job-hunting miners.
Today, Mr Rooney says, the prospects are 'dire' for those facing redundancy
from East Durham's last pits, Vane Tempest and Easington. The two pits
employed 2,300 men when they were earmarked for closure last October. 'There
are no jobs around. It will create a lot of problems with a lot of miners
unemployed. And for the young ones coming up now there's nothing.'
Mr Rooney did not find the job he wanted easily. He tried to get work on the
Channel tunnel project, but failed. He endured repetitive engineering jobs
and was made redundant a second time by a Sunderland cranemaker. He had been
on the dole for 10 months before his wife, a school cook, spotted the
crucial advertisement.
His warden's job may be a 'dream' but it is no idyll. To protect his
coastline he has had to confront youths with airguns, and flytippers.
For Pounds 10,000 a year he works far beyond his official 39 hours a week.
When he is not out with his mongrel Sabre and lurcher Bracken patrolling, or
supervising volunteers, he lectures to schools and clubs and studies for a
conservation qualification.
Yet it has worked out well. Mr Rooney used part of his Pounds 18,000 pit
redundancy to buy his terraced ex-colliery house in Seaham, a Durham coastal
town which until recently had three pits. That way, he figured, his family
would have a home whatever happened. Coalmining was never an option for his
sons. One is a care worker in a home for young delinquents and the other a
council gardener.
Mr Rooney loves his job's combination of freedom and responsibility, and the
chance it gives him to enhance the very coastline his former industry has
desecrated for the past century with colliery waste. In recent years 1.5m
tonnes of waste annually has been tipped on to the beaches from British
Coal's coastal Durham pits, turning once-golden sand into a black quagmire
so vile it featured in the film Alien Three. British Coal argued that the
costs of other disposal methods would have to be borne by the collieries,
rendering them uneconomic.
'From a conservation point of view it doesn't upset me the collieries are
closing, but from the jobs point of view it does,' says Mr Rooney. 'It's a
pity they have to close because there's nothing to replace them.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
