<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / The Coal White Paper: 'Greens' give grudging welcome
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS gave a grudging welcome yesterday to the white paper's
acknowledgement that 'in the longer term environmental pressures will
operate against coal as a primary source of energy'.
The environmental damage caused by coal burning is well-recognised - the
emission of carbon dioxide, thought to be implicated in global warming, with
sulphur dioxide which contributes to acid rain, and nitrogen oxides which
cause breathing difficulties.
The white paper concedes that it is impossible to say whether its measures
will lead to more coal being burnt in the UK. That depends on British Coal's
success in winning more sales with the benefit of the new subsidies.
But Mr Dieter Helm, director of Oxford Economic Research Associates, said:
'The effect of the subsidies is likely to be the displacement of overseas
coal imports with British coal - the total coalburn in the UK may not go
up.'
Environmentalists welcomed the smaller role given to orimulsion because of
its high sulphur content. The white paper expects an annual reduction in
orimulsion use of at least 500,000 tonnes equivalent of coal.
The Campaign for the Protection of Rural England also warmed to the
shrinking share of opencast coal mining. The paper accepts British Coal's
projections of a fall in opencast output from the current 16m tonnes to less
than 12m tonnes in 1997-98.
However, sharp differences emerged between the government and pressure
groups over which fuels would replace coal in the long term.
The white paper says: 'Some of the groups found themselves attempting to
reconcile a wish for strict emissions targets, and hence a wish to phase out
all fossil fuel burning, with a dislike for the nuclear option and support
for coal in the short term. They were able to do so only by implausible
assumptions about the speed at which renewables and energy efficiency could
contribute.'
Friends of the Earth and other groups attacked the statement that there was
no reason to close down Magnox nuclear reactors prematurely.
The white paper supported long-term research into clean-coal technology,
which strips coal-burning power stations' emissions of many of their
damaging components - although not carbon dioxide - but warned that the
present cost made it uneconomic.
Up to Pounds 12m of new research funds will go over next three years to
British Coal's Research Establishment.
Friends of the Earth called the paper's encouragement for renewable energy -
wind and wave power - 'a glimmer of light'. The paper has accepted the
recommendation of last year's advisory group that the UK should try to have
1,500MW of new electricity generating capacity from renewables by the year
2000.
</TEXT>
