<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / The Coal White Paper: Reprieves may not last three years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TRANSFORMATION in the British coal industry was set in motion by
yesterday's white paper. But in three years' time the industry under British
Coal - or its successors after the privatisation promised yesterday - may be
little different in size and efficiency from what the government envisaged
before the pit crisis developed.
Public pressure has forced a reprieve for most of the 31 pits originally
earmarked for closure. But in many cases the reprieve will be temporary and
in some cases it will last perhaps less than a year.
Radical changes in working practices were outlined in the white paper. For
example the 1908 restriction on hours worked underground will be removed.
But privatisation may have made these changes inevitable.
The changes will help British Coal to become more competitive, but it will
struggle to match the prices of its international competitors by the time of
privatisation, probably in two or three years.
If it proves impossible, PowerGen and National Power will look abroad once
more for whatever coal they need above the 'base tonnage' contracts that
must be signed by the end of the month.
By 1995 the coal industry will have to compete with increasing amounts of
nuclear power and, more importantly, gas-fired electricity. The chances of
keeping all 31 surviving pits open after two years, let alone re-opening the
seven which were mothballed yesterday, seem remote.
Negotiations between British Coal and the electricity generators will
continue on additional tonnages above the base contracts. There was nothing
in yesterday's document, however, likely to persuade the electricity
industry to take anything like the 65.5m tonnes over five years which the
government originally hoped for.
Even 40m tonnes will be difficult following the imposition of value added
tax on domestic fuel prices, which will depress the demand for coal.
What has become clear, however, is that the government is setting a course
for gradual privatisation of the coal industry by selling off both the 12
pits which are definitely to close and the seven which are to be mothballed.
In the meantime British Coal's powers over potential competitors will be
reduced by the establishment of an independent coal authority, which will
take over the corporation's role of supervising licensees.
British Coal was sanguine about the white paper's outcome. Mr Neil Clarke,
chairman, said: 'We accept that the white paper represents the best outcome
from the review that can be achieved.'
British Coal anticipates that the closure of the two collieries and the
mothballing of the seven will lead to the loss of about 5,800 jobs. This
compares with more than 30,000 envisaged in October, although more than
8,000 have left the industry since then.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Michael Heseltine
Trade &amp; industry secretary
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
'I have done all that I reasonably could, consistent with economic
realities and legal constraints, to increase the opportunities for
British Coal. The outcome will be settled. . .in the market place.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Norman Willis
TUC general secretary
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
'The White Paper is a deliberate deception. What is on offer is nothing
more than a political confidence trick which seeks to cover up the truth
that in two years the British coal industry will be dead and buried.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
