<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / The Coal White Paper: Relief as Heseltine offers haven from
Tories' political storms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER NARROW shaft of sunlight has broken through the dark grey clouds
that have overshadowed the government for a full six months. Yesterday the
mood of relief on the Conservative benches was palpable.
Mr Michael Heseltine's highly political compromise on coal may signal the
beginning of a much-needed period of calm for Mr John Major's embattled
administration.
Obstacles undoubtedly lie ahead, not least the Newbury by-election. But the
whiff of optimism in the economic indicators, the successful attempt on
Wednesday to accelerate the Maastricht ratification process and what looks
set to be an escape from the mire of the coalfields has raised Conservative
spirits.
In the parliamentary lobbies last night government business managers were
openly confident about Monday's coal debate.
There may well be continued muffled Tory backbench criticism that the
government ever found itself in such trouble, but the reassertion of
divisions along party lines in the Commons chamber suggested that
traditional political antagonisms over coal have been re-established.
The trade and industry secretary started his statement hesitantly. But it
was soon apparent that the widely leaked formula for the pits should prove
to be enough to secure Monday's vote.
Mr Robin Cook, Labour's trade spokesman warned: 'This is not a rescue plan,
merely a stay of execution,' adding that it might 'buy off' the Tory benches
but would not do the same for the country. But the attack appeared only to
restore Mr Heseltine's confidence as he shouted over heckling that the state
of Britain's coal industry was largely the fault of the last Labour
government.
When Dr Michael Clark, Tory MP for Rochford and a rebel in October, rose to
speak, it was clear he had been won round. Less positively, another Tory
rebel, Mrs Elizabeth Peacock, MP for Batley and Spen, seemed to be shifting
back towards the government, while raising some doubt as to whether enough
had been done to find new coal markets.
But of the original six Tory rebels and five abstainers only Mr Richard
Alexander, the Newark MP, appeared ready to continue defying the whips when
he warned of the 'devastation' which closures would bring to Nottinghamshire
pits.
It was also apparent that party politics was back in harness within the
trade and industry committee.
While Mr Richard Caborn, the Labour chairman, and Mr Malcolm Bruce, the
Liberal Democrat, both made their continuing dissatisfaction known, several
Tories, such as Dr Keith Hampson, a long-time Heseltine loyalist, insisted
that the broad thrust of the committee's demands had been met.
At the weekly meeting of the Tory backbench 1922 committee last night there
was a distinct sense that, for the first time since last year's 'autumn of
banana skins', a hint of spring has broken through.
</TEXT>
