<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / The Coal White Paper: Ground is laid for full privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Coal has been told to prepare for full privatisation. The government
intends to sell all British Coal's commercial operations to the
private-sector, and is proposing a new form of regulatory structure. A bill
is expected in the next session of parliament beginning in the autumn.
The crucial element will be separation of the regulatory and mining
functions of British Coal to remove the potentially serious conflict of
interest which could arise from British Coal licensing competitors.
A new public body, the Coal Authority, will be responsible for licensing all
coal mining activity. The authority, which will be prohibited from mining,
will have its headquarters in Nottinghamshire.
The white paper says there are clear benefits to the coal industry and to
consumers in freeing the industry's managers from the constraints of
public-sector ownership.
'It is to a large extent these constraints that have brought British Coal to
its present position, and there can be no confidence that within them the
industry will achieve the dramatic changes necessary if it is to have a
long-term future,' it says.
The government wants transfers to the private sector to be implemented as
quickly as possible once the legislation is passed. British Coal will also
be prepared to consider proposals for the sale of regional coal mining
packages as well as the sale of individual pits.
The white paper view that there were considerable attractions to giving
private-sector mining companies the opportunity to run pits that would
otherwise close was welcomed warmly, though cautiously, by the companies.
Many private mining groups were enthusiastic. Mr Richard Budge, chairman of
RJB Mining, which operates two deep coal mines in north-west England, said
it was a 'very balanced result' which would give subsidies to both the
public and private sectors.
He said of privatisation: 'It's not a question of cutting wages - it's a
change of culture that matters. With the commitment of our workers it would
be bound to be a success.'
Mr Malcolm Edwards, former British Coal marketing director who hopes to lead
a consortium to licence up to four mines in the Yorkshire region, said coal
buyers would warmly welcome alternative suppliers of UK coal, as British
Coal had not always been able to supply some specialised markets.
'We can't make an immediate commitment - we are miles from that. All we can
do is express a genuine commercial interest and say what could be done.'
Hanson, one of the companies most frequently named as a potential buyer, was
particularly cautious. All a spokesman would say was: 'Until we have more
information it is difficult for us to reach any decision, so we do not
register interest or disinterest until details are clearer.'
</TEXT>
